The concept of "crepuscular activity"—increased movement during dawn and dusk—affects both animal and human performance. I've documented how driver alertness patterns mirror natural biological rhythms, with increased incident rates during early morning and late afternoon hours when circadian rhythms naturally dip.

The **[mountain shuttle services](https://expresscoloradotransportation.com/shuttle-from-denver-airport-to-aspen/)** that prioritize safety understand these biological factors and schedule accordingly. They build in rest breaks during low-alertness periods, rotate drivers to maintain fresh attention, and avoid pushing through natural energy lows that increase risk.

